  crosslink: { title: "Also check your CGT main residence exemption — FRCGW stacks with other property rules.", body: "The 15% withholding applies regardless of whether the property is your main residence. If it is your main residence, you may not owe CGT at all — but you still need the clearance certificate. If you are selling an investment property, CGT is also due. Different rules apply. Running both checks together is faster than discovering a separate CGT issue after settlement.", url: "/au/check/cgt-main-residence", label: "Check your main residence exemption →" },
  lawBarSummary: "Foreign Resident Capital Gains Withholding (FRCGW): Effective 1 January 2025, the ATO withholds 15% of the sale price on the disposal of an Australian property unless the seller provides a clearance certificate. The threshold is $0 — every property sale is in scope. The previous threshold ($750,000) and rate (12.5%) expired on 31 December 2024. The clearance certificate is issued by the ATO (no fee) and confirms the seller is exempt from withholding (typically for Australian tax residents). Processing time: 1–4 weeks. The certificate must be in the buyer's solicitor's office BEFORE settlement — after settlement, withholding is automatic and the cash is locked up with the buyer pending ATO refund (6–18 months). Foreign residents must apply for a variation certificate (longer process). Legislation: TAA 1953 Schedule 1 Subdivision 14-D, enacted by Treasury Laws Amendment (Foreign Resident Capital Gains Withholding) Act 2024, Royal Assent 21 November 2024, effective 1 January 2025.",
  lawBarBadges: ["ATO", "TAA 1953 Subdiv 14-D", "Effective 1 Jan 2025", "Applies to ALL property sales", "15% withholding rate"],
  calculatorRuleBox: { label: "The rule — changed 1 January 2025", body: "From 1 January 2025, the ATO withholds 15% of the sale price on the disposal of an Australian property. The threshold is $0 — every property sale applies. The previous rule (threshold $750k, rate 12.5%) expired on 31 December 2024. The seller must obtain an ATO clearance certificate to prevent withholding. The certificate must be issued and provided to the buyer's solicitor BEFORE settlement. If the certificate has not arrived before settlement, the buyer's solicitor must withhold 15% from the seller's proceeds. Processing takes 1–4 weeks. Source: TAA 1953 Schedule 1 Subdivision 14-D." },
  calculatorClarification: { label: "Settlement date is the hard deadline — not application date, not expected issue date", body: "The clearance certificate must be in the buyer's solicitor's office BEFORE 9 am on settlement day. Settlement is locked into the contract — you cannot delay it to wait for the certificate. If the certificate arrives AFTER settlement, the buyer has already withheld 15%. That cash is then held pending the ATO refund (6–18 months). Application takes 1–4 weeks. For a settlement more than 28 days away, apply now. For a settlement within 28 days, contact the ATO immediately — the application may still be approved on an urgent basis, or you may need to request an extension from the buyer (rare but sometimes possible)." },
